1. What is an Array? (Basic)

An array is a collection of elements of the same data type, stored in continuous memory locations.

Example:

int[] arr = {10, 20, 30, 40};

2. Why Do We Use Arrays?

To store multiple values in one variable
To reduce memory usage
To access elements using indexing
To process data easily using loops
To make algorithms easier to implement (sorting, searching, etc.)

3. Indexing

Array indexing always starts from 0.

For int[] arr = {5, 10, 15}:

arr[0] = 5

arr[1] = 10

arr[2] = 15

4. Array Declaration and Initialization
Method 1: Declare first, assign later
int[] arr = new int[5];

Method 2: Declare and assign together
int[] arr = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};

5. Basic Array Operations
Access element:
arr[2];

Update element:
arr[1] = 50;

Length of array:
arr.length;

6. Traversing an Array
Using normal for loop:
for(int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    System.out.println(arr[i]);
}

Using for-each loop:
for(int value : arr) {
    System.out.println(value);
}

7. Types of Arrays
One-dimensional:
int[] a = new int[5];

Two-dimensional (matrix):
int[][] matrix = new int[3][3];

Multi-dimensional:
int[][][] data = new int[2][3][4];

8. Taking Input in Array
Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
int[] arr = new int[5];

for(int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    arr[i] = sc.nextInt();
}

9. Advantages of Arrays

Fast access using index (O(1))
Easy to traverse
Useful for mathematical and algorithmic problems

10. Disadvantages of Arrays

Fixed size
Difficult to insert or delete elements (O(n))
Only same data type allowed

11. Time Complexity of Array Operations
Operation	Time Complexity
Access element	O(1)
Update element	O(1)
Search element	O(n)
Insert element	O(n)
Delete element	O(n)
12. 2D Array Basics (Medium Level)
Declaration:
int[][] arr = new int[3][3];

Accessing element:
arr[0][1];

Traversing 2D array:
for(int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    for(int j = 0; j < arr[i].length; j++) {
        System.out.print(arr[i][j] + " ");
    }
}

13. Important Array Problems (Medium to Advanced)

Common problems you will see in DSA and interviews:

Find maximum/minimum element

Linear search

Binary search

Reverse an array

Rotate an array

Count frequency of elements

Kadaneâ€™s algorithm (maximum subarray sum)

Prefix sum

Sliding window problems

Sorting (Bubble, Selection, QuickSort)

Two-pointer problems

14. Advanced Array Concepts
1. Two Pointer Technique
Used for sorted arrays, pair problems, removing duplicates, etc.

2. Prefix Sum Array
Used to perform fast range-sum queries.

3. Sliding Window
Used to find maximum or minimum values in a continuous range.

4. Searching Techniques
Linear search (unsorted arrays)
Binary search (sorted arrays)

5. Sorting Techniques

Bubble Sort
Selection Sort
Insertion Sort
QuickSort
MergeSort

6. Dynamic Array

In Java, the dynamic array is implemented using:
ArrayList

15. Quick Revision Notes

Array stores same type of data
Index starts from 0
Stored in continuous memory
size is fixed
Fast access (O(1))
Insertion/deletion is slow (O(n))
1D, 2D, and multi-dimensional arrays exist